# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] The **1877 Boston Red Caps season** was the seventh season of the franchise.
[src:1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] Arthur Soden became the new owner of the franchise, who won their first National League pennant.
[src:1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The **1878 Boston Red Caps season** was the eighth season of the franchise.
[src:1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The Red Caps won their second straight National League pennant.
[src:1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1879-providence-grays-season] The **1879 Providence Grays** won the National League title in only their second season in the league.
[src:1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1880 Chicago White Stockings season** was the ninth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the fifth in the National League and the third at Lakefront Park.
[src:1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 67–17.
[src:1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1881 Chicago White Stockings season** was the tenth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the sixth in the National League and the fourth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 56–28.
[src:1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1882 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 11th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the seventh in the National League and the fifth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 55–29, 3 games ahead of the second place Providence Grays.
[src:1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The **1909 Pittsburgh Pirates season** was the 28th season for the Pittsburgh Pirates franchise, during which they won the National League pennant with a record of 110–42 and their first World Series over the Detroit Tigers.
[src:1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Led by shortstop Honus Wagner and outfielder-manager Fred Clarke, the Pirates scored the most runs in the majors.
[src:1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Wagner led the league in batting average, on-base percentage, slugging percentage, and runs batted in.
[src:1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Pirates owner Barney Dreyfuss opened the Pirates' new ballpark, named Forbes Field, on June 30, 1909.
[src:1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The Pirates' 110 wins remain a team record, a record they set in the last game of the season by beating the Cincinnati Reds 7–4 in muddy conditions on October 5.
[src:1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season] It is in fact the best regular season win percentage by any World Series winning team.
[src:1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season] In the World Series, Pittsburgh faced the American League champion Detroit Tigers, led by triple crown winner Ty Cobb.
[src:1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The matchup was largely billed as one between the major leagues' two superstars.
[src:1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Wagner thoroughly outplayed Cobb, and rookie Babe Adams won all three of his starts, as the Pirates won in seven games.
